4  Demonstrate port mapping and verify running containers using docker ps.

# *STEP 1 — Create a project in Eclipse*

1. Open *Eclipse*
2. Go to *File → New → Project*
3. Select *General → Project*
4. Name it: my-web-app
5. Click *Finish*

---

# *STEP 2 — Add your files*

Inside your project → right-click → *New → File*

### Create server.js:

js
const http = require("http");

const server = http.createServer((req, res) => {
    res.end("Hello from Dockerized Web App!");
});

server.listen(3000, () => {
    console.log("Server running on port 3000");
});


### Create Dockerfile:

dockerfile
FROM node:18
WORKDIR /app
COPY . .
EXPOSE 3000
CMD ["node", "server.js"]


That’s it. Eclipse is just acting as a text editor here.

---

# *STEP 3 — Open Terminal inside Eclipse*

### Option A: Use Eclipse Terminal view

Go to:


Window → Show View → Terminal


Click *Open Terminal* → choose your project directory.

### Option B: Use Windows CMD/PowerShell

Navigate manually:


cd C:\Users\pooji\EclipseWorkspace\my-web-app


---

# *STEP 4 — Build Docker Image*

Run this in the terminal:


docker build -t my-web-app .


---

# *STEP 5 — Run the Docker Container*


docker run -d -p 8080:3000 my-web-app


Then open browser:


http://localhost:8080


---

# *STEP 6 — Check Running Containers*


docker ps


You’ll see:


CONTAINER ID   IMAGE        PORTS                    STATUS
xxxxxxx        my-web-app   0.0.0.0:8080->3000/tcp   Up 
